    <name>
      <text>Finding the Radius of a Circle with Given Center and Point on the Circumference</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Suppose the center of a circle is \(O({@center[1]@},{@center[2]@})\) and \(P({@point[1]@},{@point[2]@})\) is a point on the circle. What is the radius of the circle?</p>
<p>Radius \(=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>
<p>To find the radius of the circle, we can use the distance formula between the center of the circle \((C)\) and any point  (\(P)\) on the circle. </p><p>The distance formula between two points \((x_1, y_1)\) and \((x_2, y_2)\) is given by:</p>
<p>\( \text{Distance} = \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2} \)</p>
<p>In this case, the center of the circle is \(O({@center[1]@},{@center[2]@})\) and the point on the circle is  \(P({@point[1]@},{@point[2]@})\). </p>
<p>Let's substitute these values into the formula:</p>
<p>\( \begin{align} \text{Radius} &= \sqrt{({@point[1]@} - {@center[1]@})^2 + ({@point[2]@} - {@center[2]@})^2} \\
                                           &= \sqrt{({@expr1@})^2 + ({@expr2@})^2} \\
                                          &= \sqrt{{@expr3@} + {@expr4@}} \\
                                          & = \sqrt{{@expr5@}} \\
                                        [[ if test='integerp(sqrt(expr5))' ]] 
                                        &= {@radius@} \\
\text{Therefore, the radius of the circle is} \,{@radius@} \,  \text{units.}
                                       [[ else ]]
                                      &  \approx {@expr6@}  \\
\text{Therefore, the radius of the circle is approximately}\,  {@expr6@} \, \text{units.}
                                      [[/ if]]   \end{align} \) </p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
